{
  "body": "Act as a professional watercolor painter and art teacher. Generate a 4-step watercolor painting tutorial guide for: {{subject_descriptor}}. Maintain a clean, instructional, editorial illustration style consistent with high-quality watercolor tutorial books and Skillshare-class course materials.\n\n— Layout (CRITICAL — follow exactly) —\n2×2 grid of four equal-size panels showing the painting process, with a central diagram inset where the four panels meet:\n\n  ┌──────────────┬──────────────┐\n  │  Panel 1 (TL)│  Panel 2 (TR)│\n  │              │              │\n  │     ┌────────┴────────┐     │\n  ├─────┤  Central diagram├─────┤\n  │     └────────┬────────┘     │\n  │              │              │\n  │  Panel 3 (BL)│  Panel 4 (BR)│\n  └──────────────┴──────────────┘\n\nEach of the 4 panels shows the SAME {{subject}} progressively painted further. The central inset overlaps the meeting corners and shows {{central_diagram_focus}} as a clean pencil/line sketch with thin labels and small arrows.\n\n— Step content (text labels in {{label_language}}) —\nPanel 1 (top-left) — \"{{step1_label}}\":\n   Action description: {{step1_action}}\n   Show the {{subject}} at the base-wash / underpainting stage.\n\nPanel 2 (top-right) — \"{{step2_label}}\":\n   Action description: {{step2_action}}\n   Show the {{subject}} with form/texture starting to emerge.\n\nPanel 3 (bottom-left) — \"{{step3_label}}\":\n   Action description: {{step3_action}}\n   Show the {{subject}} with deeper layers and shadow definition added.\n\nPanel 4 (bottom-right) — \"{{step4_label}}\":\n   Action description: {{step4_action}}\n   Show the COMPLETED finished {{subject}} painting.\n\n— Color swatches (next to each step) —\nNext to each panel, paint a small column of round / square watercolor swatches representing the colors used in that step. Hand-letter the pigment name beside each swatch in small clean type. Use these pigments overall: {{color_palette}}. Distribute them logically across the 4 steps (lighter / base colors in early steps, deeper accent colors in later steps).\n\n— Central diagram —\nA crisp pencil-style line sketch of the {{subject}} placed in the center where the 4 panels meet, slightly overlapping their corners. The diagram should show {{central_diagram_focus}}. Include thin arrows indicating light direction, and small labels (1–3 words each) marking key anatomical / structural parts. Sketch lines are graphite-grey, NOT watercolor.\n\n— Style —\n{{background_paper}} background visible as the canvas of the entire image. Soft watercolor illustration aesthetic — visible pigment granulation, bleeding edges, slight color blooms. Clean editorial labels and arrows in fine sans-serif type ({{label_language}}). Vertical composition, 4K ultra-high-definition. Whole image feels like a single page from a premium watercolor tutorial book (think Felix Scheinberger / Liron Yanconsky / Anna Mason instructional spreads).\n\n— Typography —\nAll labels in {{label_language}}, set in a clean modern sans-serif (or its CJK equivalent for Chinese / Japanese / Korean). Step titles are slightly larger and bolder. Action descriptions are smaller, set in 2–3 short lines per panel. Pigment names beside swatches are smallest size. All text is hand-drawn-looking but legible — NOT machine-printed feel.\n\n— Composition —\nCaptured in {{aspect_ratio}} aspect ratio. Generous breathing space around each panel. The 4 panels are visually separated by thin pencil lines or subtle empty gutters — NOT hard black borders. The whole spread feels relaxed and educational, not cramped.\n\n— Additional details —\n{{extra_notes}}\n\n— Strictly avoid —\n- Do NOT show different subjects in different panels — the {{subject}} progresses through the SAME painting across 4 stages\n- Do NOT use photo-realistic rendering — this is hand-painted watercolor with visible brush marks\n- Do NOT use heavy black borders, drop shadows, or 3D bevels around panels\n- Do NOT generate gibberish text or fake glyphs in the labels — if uncertain in CJK, prefer fewer clearer words over many broken ones\n- Do NOT add modern UI elements (rounded buttons, gradients, icons) — this is a paper tutorial spread, not a screen\n- Do NOT add color outside the {{color_palette}} list (except for graphite pencil grey on the central diagram)\n- Do NOT use rainbow or neon colors unless they are explicitly in the palette\n- Do NOT add watermarks, logos, signatures (unless specified in extra_notes)\n- Do NOT crowd the central diagram with too many labels — keep it diagrammatic and breathable\n- Do NOT add extra panels, borders, mockup-frame elements, or page-curl effects\n\n— Output —\nDirect image output. Vertical composition, 4K resolution, print-ready quality. Should look like a single beautiful page from a watercolor instructional book.\n\nKeywords: watercolor tutorial, step-by-step painting guide, art education, instructional illustration, 4-panel layout, color swatches, watercolor painter, painting class, soft watercolor, paper texture, editorial illustration",
